choices.text:
"why are people not trying to solve the problems we currently have with greenhouse gases and food waste, instead of arguing unnecessarily about "alternative facts" and denying that there are problems in the first place".

As a child in Denmark, my biggest problem was "why are people so rich that they can build the huge homes they live in when there are so many poor people out there". I grew up thinking that everyone must have a house as big as mom's. I still find it hard to understand why people's appearance or their social position in society is more valuable on a value chart than life itself.

 As a child in Denmark, my biggest problem was "WHY DO PEOPLE LIE TO EACH OTHER". 

When I was a kid I noticed one day that when I told the truth, most people were really mad at me for hurting them. I felt bad for telling the truth, and I kept asking myself what I was doing wrong. Turns out that I actually should trust my gut. My gut had always been right when it came to these things, but I kept dismissing those inner voices because people were angry at me for telling the truth.

By the time I went to school, both my best friend and my favorite aunt had parents who had overnight "positively" convinced themselves that they did not want their offspring anymore, and so they made me believe that everything was going to be fine. The very next day I was told the truth.
